snippet.textDisplay:
about ten years ago I got obsessed with the mandelbrot set and developed a whole family of tiny apps that plots the set in various ways. my favorite has always been the buddhabrot set, which plots the cumulative trails of escape paths of numbers which do not belong in the set. And using a false coloring technique similar to astrophotography on it makes the final result look like a nebula. I wish I had the code online right now but at least this is one of the desktop wallpapers that I've been using for literally a decade. https://www.dropbox.com/s/e24pild8pcwwgbf/buddhabrot_1050x1680.jpg?dl=0


Now that you've shown the bifurcation on the z axis, I think you've given my currently dormant hobby a new life.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey there! I've done some applied research in physics with models that present that same bifurcation behavior (although using functions different from the logistic function). However, although I understand the physical causes (in my systems) for period doubling and quadrupling, its very hard (for me) to understand the transition to chaos... In the back of my mind I've always suspected (intuitively) that some of the bifurcation behavior we see in those types of diagrams are tied to the fact that computations have finite precision, and that at some point the solution is so sensible from the function value that a rounding in the 10^-32 decimal number will make a difference (and create a bifurcation). I have not tried to prove any of this and its just a hunch based on the level of sensitivity that some physical systems show as you advance them in time (accounting for all the past information)... By the way, congrats on the channel. Very, very interesting!
